# Harness MCP Tool Calling Skill

## ⚠️ CRITICAL: MCP Protocol Initialization is MANDATORY

**Before calling ANY MCP tool in a new session, you MUST initialize the MCP protocol.**

If you skip this, MCP tools will return generic "An error occurred" errors.

### Required Initialization (Do This First)

In every new session that will call MCP tools, execute this code **before any `tools/call` method invocations**:

```powershell
$ServerUrl = "http://127.0.0.1:5081/"
$Headers = @{ "Accept" = "application/json, text/event-stream" }

function Invoke-McpRequest {
    param ([string]$Method, [object]$Params = @{}, [int]$Id = 1)
    $body = @{
        jsonrpc = "2.0"
        id = $Id
        method = $Method
        params = $Params
    } | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 10

    $response = Invoke-WebRequest -Uri $ServerUrl -Method Post `
        -ContentType "application/json" -Headers $Headers `
        -Body $body -UseBasicParsing -TimeoutSec 10

    $raw = $response.Content
    $dataLine = ($raw -split "`n") | Where-Object { $_ -match "^data:" } | Select-Object -First 1
    $json = $dataLine -replace "^data:\s*", ""
    return $json | ConvertFrom-Json
}

# Step 1: Initialize MCP protocol
$initResult = Invoke-McpRequest -Method "initialize" -Params @{
    protocolVersion = "2024-11-05"
    capabilities = @{}
    clientInfo = @{ name = "claude-agent"; version = "1.0" }
} -Id 1

# Step 2: Send initialized notification (required by MCP spec)
$null = Invoke-McpRequest -Method "initialized" -Params @{} -Id 0

# Now you can call MCP tools
```

**Why this is required:**
- MCP (Model Context Protocol) requires a handshake before tool calls
- Step 1 (`initialize`) establishes the protocol contract
- Step 2 (`initialized`) signals the client is ready
- Only after both steps can `tools/call` succeed

